entry.title: Online Retail Customer Clustering with KMeans and Hierarchical Clustering

link.title: Online Retail Customer Clustering with KMeans and Hierarchical Clustering

entry.content:
Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/hellbuoy/online-retail-customer-clustering.

In this notebook, I'll try to segment customer with certain features by using KMeans and Hierarchical Clustering.

Import Module & Preview Data 

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import datetime as dt

import os
for dirname, _, filenames in os.walk('/kaggle/input'):
    for filename in filenames:
        print(os.path.join(dirname, filename))

/kaggle/input/online-retail-customer-clustering/OnlineRetail.csv

df = pd.read_csv('/kaggle/input/online-retail-customer-clustering/OnlineRetail.csv', sep=',', encoding='ISO-8859-1', header=0)
df.head()

Since only 24,92% values are missing, we can drop them as it won't ruin our model.

df.dropna(inplace=True)
df.shape

(406829, 8)

We need to convert CustomerID as string, because it's not a number from business viewpoint.

df['CustomerID'] = df['CustomerID'].astype(str)

Feature Engineering

We'll create 3 new column to see the clusters between them:

  • Amount: Total money spent by a customer
  • Frequency: How many times a customer made transactions
  • Recency: The last time a customer made a transaction
df['Amount'] = df['Quantity'] * df['UnitPrice']
df_1 = df.groupby('CustomerID')['Amount'].sum()
df_1 = df_1.reset_index()
df_1.head()
CustomerID Amount

1 12347.0 4310.00
2 12348.0 1797.24
3 12349.0 1757.55
4 12350.0 334.40 
df_2 = df.groupby('CustomerID')['InvoiceNo'].count()
df_2 = df_2.reset_index()
df_2.columns = ['CustomerID', 'Frequency']
df_2.head()
CustomerID Frequency
0 12346.0 2
1 12347.0 182
2 12348.0 31
3 12349.0 73

df['InvoiceDate'] = pd.to_datetime(df['InvoiceDate'], format='%d-%m-%Y %H:%M')

max_date = max(df['InvoiceDate'])

df['Diff'] = (max_date - df['InvoiceDate']).dt.days

1 12347.0 1
2 12348.0 74

Now we can merge the 3 mini dataframes.

new_df = pd.merge(df_1, df_2, on='CustomerID', how='inner')
new_df = pd.merge(new_df, df_3, on='CustomerID', how='inner')
new_df.columns = ['CustomerID', 'Amount', 'Frequency', 'Recency']
new_df.head()
CustomerID Amount Frequency Recency

We can see that there are many outliers looking at the std is much bigger than 75% quantile of the data.

Q1 = new_df['Amount'].quantile(0.05)
Q3 = new_df['Amount'].quantile(0.95)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
new_df = new_df[(new_df['Amount'] >= Q1 - 1.5 * IQR) & (new_df['Amount'] <= Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)]

Q1 = new_df['Frequency'].quantile(0.05)
Q3 = new_df['Frequency'].quantile(0.95)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
new_df = new_df[(new_df['Frequency'] >= Q1 - 1.5 * IQR) & (new_df['Frequency'] <= Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)]

Q1 = new_df['Recency'].quantile(0.05)
Q3 = new_df['Recency'].quantile(0.95)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
new_df = new_df[(new_df['Recency'] >= Q1 - 1.5 * IQR) & (new_df['Recency'] <= Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)]

Let's see the pairplot of feature engineered DataFrame.

sns.pairplot(new_df[['Amount', 'Frequency', 'Recency']])

<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x7f9eacf30990>

Clustering with KMeans 

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

x = new_df[['Amount', 'Frequency', 'Recency']]

scaler = StandardScaler()
new_df_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(x)
new_df_scaled = pd.DataFrame(new_df_scaled)
new_df_scaled.columns = ['Amount', 'Frequency', 'Recency']
new_df_scaled.head()
Amount Frequency Recency
0 -0.723738 -0.752888 2.301611
1 1.731617 1.042467 -0.906466
2 0.300128 -0.463636 -0.183658
3 0.277517 -0.044720 -0.738141
4 -0.533235 -0.603275 2.143188

We'll use the elbow method to find optimal number of clusters.

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

inertias = []
for i in range(1,11):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=21)
    km.fit(new_df_scaled)
    inertias.append(km.inertia_)
    
plt.plot(range(1,11), inertias)
plt.title('Elbow Method using Inertia')
plt.xlabel('No of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')

Text(0, 0.5, 'Inertia')
km = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=21)
km.fit(new_df_scaled)

KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=21)
km.labels_

array([1, 0, 2, ..., 1, 2, 2], dtype=int32)
new_df['Cluster'] = km.labels_
new_df.head()
CustomerID Amount Frequency Recency Cluster
0 12346.0 0.00 2 325 1
1 12347.0 4310.00 182 1 0
2 12348.0 1797.24 31 74 2
3 12349.0 1757.55 73 18 2
4 12350.0 334.40 17 309 1

We'll see & plot the pairplot later, as we want to compare it with hierarchical clustering.

Clustering with Hierarchical Clustering 

from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import linkage
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram

mergings = linkage(new_df_scaled, method='average', metric='euclidean')
dendrogram(mergings)
plt.show()

We see that the red line is when number of cluster are optimal, so we'll cut the tree into 3 clusters.

from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import cut_tree

cluster_id = cut_tree(mergings, n_clusters=3).reshape(-1,)
cluster_id

array([0, 0, 0, ..., 0, 0, 0])
new_df1 = new_df.copy()
new_df1['Cluster'] = cluster_id

Comparing the Clustering Algorithm 

ax = sns.pairplot(new_df[['Amount', 'Frequency', 'Recency', 'Cluster']], hue='Cluster')
ax.fig.suptitle('KMeans Clustering', y=1.08, fontsize=18)

Text(0.5, 1.08, 'KMeans Clustering')
ax = sns.pairplot(new_df1[['Amount', 'Frequency', 'Recency', 'Cluster']], hue='Cluster')
ax.fig.suptitle('Hierarchical Clustering', y=1.08, fontsize=18)

Text(0.5, 1.08, 'Hierarchical Clustering')

Amount vs Recency 

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.scatterplot(x='Recency', y='Amount', hue='Cluster', data=new_df, palette='bright')
plt.title('From KMeans Clustering')
plt.ylim(0,)

(0.0, 14575.851)
  • Cluster 0: Spent around >3K and recently made transaction.
  • Cluster 1: Not spent much money and we didn't see them for a relatively long time.
  • Cluster 2: Not spent much money but still fresh customers.

Frequency vs Recency 

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.scatterplot(x='Recency', y='Frequency', hue='Cluster', data=new_df, palette='bright')
plt.title('From KMeans Clustering')
plt.ylim(0,)

(0.0, 753.85)
  • Cluster 0: Shop a lot and recently made transaction.
  • Cluster 1: Rarely shop and we didn't see them for a relatively long time.
  • Cluster 2: Rarely shop but still fresh customers.

Amount vs Frequency 

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.scatterplot(x='Amount', y='Frequency', hue='Cluster', data=new_df1, palette='bright')
plt.title('From Hierarchical Clustering')
plt.ylim(0,)

(0.0, 753.85)
  • Cluster 0: Spent around <5K and rarely made transaction.
  • Cluster 1: Average customers with fair share of amount and frequency.
  • Cluster 2: Priority customers who spent much more money and shop frequently.

From the clusters above, the online retailer can make targeted advertisements for each cluster. Thanks for reading this notebook :)

entry.title: Mall Customer Segmentation with KMeans
entry.content:
Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/vjchoudhary7/customer-segmentation-tutorial-in-python.

In this notebook, I'll do clustering using KMeans (unsupervised learning) for mall customer segmentation.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline
import seaborn as sns
sns.set(style='whitegrid')
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

pd.set_option('max_columns', None)
pd.set_option('max_rows', None)

import os
for dirname, _, filenames in os.walk('/kaggle/input'):
    for filename in filenames:
        print(os.path.join(dirname, filename))

/kaggle/input/customer-segmentation-tutorial-in-python/Mall_Customers.csv

df = pd.read_csv('/kaggle/input/customer-segmentation-tutorial-in-python/Mall_Customers.csv')
df.head()
CustomerID Gender Age Annual Income (k$) Spending Score (1-100)
0 1 Male 19 15 39
1 2 Male 21 15 81
2 3 Female 20 16 6
3 4 Female 23 16 77
4 5 Female 31 17 40 
df.describe()
CustomerID Age Annual Income (k$) Spending Score (1-100)
count 200.000000 200.000000 200.000000 200.000000
mean 100.500000 38.850000 60.560000 50.200000
std 57.879185 13.969007 26.264721 25.823522
min 1.000000 18.000000 15.000000 1.000000
25% 50.750000 28.750000 41.500000 34.750000
50% 100.500000 36.000000 61.500000 50.000000
75% 150.250000 49.000000 78.000000 73.000000
max 200.000000 70.000000 137.000000 99.000000

Let's check if there are any missing values.

df.isnull().any().any()

False
size = df['Gender'].value_counts()
plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
plt.pie(size, colors=['lightblue', 'salmon'], labels=['Female', 'Male'], shadow=True, autopct='%.2f%%', explode=[0,0.05])
plt.title('Customers Gender')

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Customers Gender')
plt.figure(figsize=(18,4))

plt.subplot(131)
sns.distplot(df['Age'])
plt.title('Distribution of Age')

plt.subplot(132)
sns.distplot(df['Annual Income (k$)'])
plt.title('Distribution of Annual Income')

plt.subplot(133)
sns.distplot(df['Spending Score (1-100)'])
plt.title('Distribution of Spending Score')

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Distribution of Spending Score')

We can see that:

  • People of age around 30-35 are the most frequent visitor.
  • There are few customers earn above 90k Dollars, with most people have annual income around 50-90k Dollars.
  • Majority of people have spending score around 40-60.
sns.heatmap(df[['Age', 'Annual Income (k$)', 'Spending Score (1-100)']].corr(), cmap='GnBu', annot=True, square=True, linewidths=0.1, linecolor='white')

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fb5d9a96a10>

We can see that there are no strong correlation around the heatmap, so it may hard to fit model such as regression for this problem.

plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))

plt.subplot(121)
sns.boxplot(x='Gender', y='Spending Score (1-100)', data=df)
plt.title('Gender vs Spending Score')

plt.subplot(122)
sns.boxplot(x='Gender', y='Annual Income (k$)', data=df)
plt.title('Gender vs Annual Income')

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Gender vs Annual Income')
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.scatterplot(x='Annual Income (k$)', y='Spending Score (1-100)', data=df)
plt.title('Annual Income vs Spending Score')

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Annual Income vs Spending Score')

The graph shows that we can segment customer into 5 clusters, but let's do that by using KMeans clustering.

KMeans has a n_clusters parameter, which is a number of cluster, that we can find the optimal n_clusters by using elbow method.

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

df_1 = df[['Annual Income (k$)', 'Spending Score (1-100)']]
inertias = []
for i in range(1,11):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=21)
    km.fit(df_1)
    inertias.append(km.inertia_)
    
plt.plot(range(1,11), inertias)
plt.title('Elbow Method using Inertia')
plt.xlabel('No of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')

Text(0, 0.5, 'Inertia')

The inertia starts decreasing slowly at 5 n_clusters, so we'll choose 5 clusters.

km = KMeans(n_clusters=5, random_state=21)
df_1['K_Means'] = km.fit_predict(df_1)

# I ran the code without the labels below first, then I name the labels based on the scatterplot
labels = ['Low Income Low Spending', 'Low Income High Spending', 'Average ', 'High Income Low Spending', 'High Income High Spending']

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.scatterplot(x='Annual Income (k$)', y='Spending Score (1-100)', hue='K_Means', data=df_1, palette='bright')
plt.legend(labels=labels, bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.title('KMeans Clustering of Annual Income vs Spending Score')

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'KMeans Clustering of Annual Income vs Spending Score')
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.scatterplot(x='Age', y='Spending Score (1-100)', data=df)
plt.title('Age vs Spending Score')

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Age vs Spending Score')

It's a bit hard to see the segmentation of Age vs Spending Score, thus we'll make use of KMeans again.

df_2 = df[['Age', 'Spending Score (1-100)']]
inertias = []
for i in range(1,11):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=21)
    km.fit(df_2)
    inertias.append(km.inertia_)
    
plt.plot(range(1,11), inertias)
plt.title('Elbow Method using Inertia')
plt.xlabel('No of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')

Text(0, 0.5, 'Inertia')
km = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=21)
df_2['K_Means'] = km.fit_predict(df_2)

# I ran the code without the labels below first, then I name the labels based on the scatterplot
labels = ['Target Customers (Young)', 'Priority Customers', 'Target Customers (Old)', 'Usual Customers']

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.scatterplot(x='Age', y='Spending Score (1-100)', hue='K_Means', data=df_2, palette='bright')
plt.legend(labels=labels, bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.title('KMeans Clustering of Age vs Spending Score')

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'KMeans Clustering of Age vs Spending Score')

To summarize, we can do clustering on unlabeled data by using KMeans, and in the process, we do some EDA and find the optimal number of clusters by using elbow method. Thanks for reading this notebook :)

entry.title: Dog and Cat Classification with CNN

link.title: Dog and Cat Classification with CNN

entry.content:
Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/c/dogs-vs-cats. In this notebook, I will try to classify dog and cat images using CNN.

Import Modules 

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline
import seaborn as sns
import random
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
from keras.preprocessing.image import load_img

pd.set_option('max_columns', None)
pd.set_option('max_rows', None)

import os
for dirname, _, filenames in os.walk('/kaggle/input'):
    for filename in filenames:
        print(os.path.join(dirname, filename))

/kaggle/input/dogs-vs-cats/train.zip
/kaggle/input/dogs-vs-cats/test1.zip
/kaggle/input/dogs-vs-cats/sampleSubmission.csv

!unzip /kaggle/input/dogs-vs-cats/train.zip -d train
!unzip /kaggle/input/dogs-vs-cats/test1.zip -d test

Archive:  /kaggle/input/dogs-vs-cats/train.zip
replace train/train/cat.0.jpg? [y]es, [n]o, [A]ll, [N]one, [r]ename: ^C
Archive:  /kaggle/input/dogs-vs-cats/test1.zip
replace test/test1/1.jpg? [y]es, [n]o, [A]ll, [N]one, [r]ename: ^C

Read extracted files and saves them as a DataFrame.

filenames = os.listdir('train/train')
categories = []
for filename in filenames: 
    category = filename.split('.')[0]
    if category == 'dog':
        categories.append(1)
    else :
        categories.append(0)

df= pd.DataFrame({'filename': filenames,
                  'category': categories})

df.head()
filename category
0 dog.10057.jpg 1
1 dog.4598.jpg 1
2 cat.8059.jpg 0
3 cat.2627.jpg 0
4 dog.7406.jpg 1 
sns.countplot(df['category'])

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f977b69ab90>

Let's check one image randomly.

sample = random.choice(filenames)
image = load_img("train/train/"+sample)
plt.imshow(image)

<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x7f977b676110>
img_width = 128
img_height = 128
img_channel = 3
img_size = (img_width, img_height)

CNN Modelling

Here I use CNN architecture with 4 stages. The first 3 stages consist of:

  • Conv2D: 2D Convolution Layer.
  • BatchNormalization: Transformation that maintains the mean output close to 0 and the output standard deviation close to 1.
  • MaxPool2D: Downsamples the input representation (reduce output shape)
  • Dropout: Probabilistically removing inputs to a layer, which may be input variables in the data sample or activations from a previous layer.
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Conv2D, BatchNormalization, MaxPool2D, Dropout, Flatten, Dense

model = Sequential()

model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=(img_width, img_height, img_channel)))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

model.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

model.add(Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))

model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='rmsprop', metrics=['accuracy'])

model.summary()

To prevent overfitting and save time, we use:

  • EarlyStopping: Allows us to specify the performance measure to monitor, the trigger, and once triggered, it will stop the training process.
  • ReduceLROnPlateau: Reduce learning rate when a metric has stopped improving.
from keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ReduceLROnPlateau

earlystop = EarlyStopping(patience=10)
lr_reduction = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_acc', patience=2,
                                 verbose=1, factor=0.5, min_lr=0.00001)
callbacks = [earlystop, lr_reduction]

Prepare Train & Validation Data

Because we will use image genaretor with class_mode="categorical". We need to convert column category into string. Then imagenerator will convert it one-hot encoding which is good for our classification.

df['category'] = df['category'].replace({0: 'cat', 1: 'dog'})

df.head()
filename category
0 dog.10057.jpg dog
1 dog.4598.jpg dog
2 cat.8059.jpg cat
3 cat.2627.jpg cat
4 dog.7406.jpg dog 
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

train_df, val_df = train_test_split(df, test_size=0.2, random_state=21)
train_df = train_df.reset_index(drop=True)
val_df = val_df.reset_index(drop=True)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,4))

plt.subplot(121)
sns.countplot(train_df['category'])

plt.subplot(122)
sns.countplot(val_df['category'])

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f977b626510>
total_train = train_df.shape[0]
total_val = val_df.shape[0]
batch_size=15

Training Generator 

from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rotation_range=15, rescale=1./255,
                                   shear_range=0.1, zoom_range=0.2,
                                   horizontal_flip=True, width_shift_range=0.1,
                                   height_shift_range=0.1)

train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_dataframe(train_df, "train/train/",
                                                    x_col='filename', y_col='category',
                                                    target_size=img_size, class_mode='categorical',
                                                    batch_size=batch_size)

Found 20000 validated image filenames belonging to 2 classes.

Validation Generator 

validation_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

                                                              x_col='filename', y_col='category',
                                                              target_size=img_size, class_mode='categorical',
                                                              batch_size=batch_size)

Fit Model 

epochs=3 if False else 30

                    validation_steps=total_val//batch_size, steps_per_epoch=total_train//batch_size,
                    callbacks=callbacks)

                                              x_col='filename', y_col=None,
                                              class_mode=None, target_size=img_size,
                                              batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=False)

Found 12500 validated image filenames.

Predict Test Data

With categorical classication, the prediction is the probabilities of each category. So we will pick the category that have the highest probability with numpy average max.

predict = model.predict_generator(test_generator, steps=np.ceil(nb_samples/batch_size))
test_df['category'] = np.argmax(predict, axis=-1)

Let's convert the predict category into dog & cat again.

label_map = dict((v,k) for k,v in train_generator.class_indices.items())
test_df['category'] = test_df['category'].replace(label_map)

Now we can see the predicted result with images.

sample_test = test_df.head(18)
sample_test.head()

    filename = row['filename']
    category = row['category']
    img = load_img("test/test1/"+filename, target_size=img_size)
    plt.subplot(6, 3, index+1)
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.xlabel(filename + ' (' + "{}".format(category) + ')' )

So far so good, except for 6779.jpg which I thought was a dumbell :D

entry.title: Predict Diamond Prices using Regression
entry.content:
Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/shivam2503/diamonds In this notebook, I will try to implement machine learning model (regression) to predict the price of diamonds. This simple notebook just focus on the EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis) and simple machine learning.

Data Description:

price: price in US dollars (326--18,823)

carat: weight of the diamond (0.2--5.01)

cut: quality of the cut (Fair, Good, Very Good, Premium, Ideal)

color: diamond colour, from J (worst) to D (best)

clarity: a measurement of how clear the diamond is (I1 (worst), SI2, SI1, VS2, VS1, VVS2, VVS1, IF (best))

x: length in mm (0--10.74)

y: width in mm (0--58.9)

z: depth in mm (0--31.8)

depth: total depth percentage = z / mean(x, y) = 2 * z / (x + y) (43--79)

table: width of top of diamond relative to widest point (43--95)

1. Data Handling

1.1 Import Module and Preview Data 

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline
import seaborn as sns
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

pd.set_option('max_columns', None)
pd.set_option('max_rows', None)

import os
for dirname, _, filenames in os.walk('/kaggle/input'):
    for filename in filenames:
        print(os.path.join(dirname, filename))

/kaggle/input/diamonds/diamonds.csv

df = pd.read_csv('/kaggle/input/diamonds/diamonds.csv')
df.head()

4 5 0.31 Good J SI2 63.3 58.0 335 4.34 4.35 2.75

We don't need 'Unnamed: 0' columns, so we can drop it.

df.drop('Unnamed: 0', axis=1, inplace=True)

df.info()

memory usage: 4.1+ MB

We can see that cut, color, and clarity are categorical features, while others are numerical.

1.2 Univariate and Bivariate Data Analysis 

plt.figure(figsize=(12,10))
sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True, square=True, cmap='RdGy', linewidths=0.1, linecolor='white')

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f97715e2d90>

We can see that x, y, z, carat have strong correlation with price, while table and depth don't have. Also, table and depth don't have a significant relation with other features as well.

1.3 Check Missing Values 

df.describe(include='all')

Values of 0 in x, y, z is not possible, because they are length, width, and depth according to the description. We'll check how many rows have that condition.

df[['x','y','z']] = df[['x', 'y', 'z']].replace(0, np.NaN)

df.isnull().sum()

dtype: int64

Since our dataset is big, dropping 20 rows shouldn't cost us.

df.dropna(inplace=True)

1.4 Categorical Data 

plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))

plt.subplot(321)
sns.countplot(x='cut', data=df, order=['Fair', 'Good', 'Very Good', 'Premium', 'Ideal'])
plt.title('Quality of the Cut Countplot')

plt.subplot(322)

plt.subplot(324)

plt.subplot(326)
sns.boxplot(x='clarity', y='price', data=df, order=['I1', 'SI2', 'SI1', 'VS2', 'VS1', 'VVS2', 'VVS1', 'IF'])
plt.title('Diamond Clarity vs Price Boxplot')

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Diamond Clarity vs Price Boxplot')

Overall, median prices are very low compared to the the highest price values for all the categories in colors, cut and clarity (and it looks like a gallery of swords). Next, we'll convert the categorical data into numerical data using one hot encoding.

For reference: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.get_dummies.html

clean_df = pd.get_dummies(df)
clean_df.head()
carat depth table price x y z cut_Fair cut_Good cut_Ideal cut_Premium cut_Very Good color_D color_E color_F color_G color_H color_I color_J clarity_I1 clarity_IF clarity_SI1 clarity_SI2 clarity_VS1 clarity_VS2 clarity_VVS1 clarity_VVS2

1.5 Data Scaling

I'll use StandardScaler, which can transform numerical data to have mean of 0 and standard deviation of 1.

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
numericals = pd.DataFrame(StandardScaler().fit_transform(clean_df[['carat','depth','x','y','z','table']]),
                        columns=['carat','depth','x','y','z','table'],
                        index=clean_df.index)

clean_df[['carat','depth','x','y','z','table']] = numericals[['carat','depth','x','y','z','table']]
clean_df.head()

It's pretty cool that the stats are still same even after standardization.

1.6 Split into Train and Test Data 

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X = clean_df.drop(['price'], axis=1)
y = clean_df['price']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=21)

2. Model Training 

from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression, Ridge, Lasso

Reference for the metrics I use: https://towardsdatascience.com/metrics-to-understand-regression-models-in-plain-english-part-1-c902b2f4156f

Reference for the explanation of Linear Regression, Ridge, and Lasso: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCtYLUTtgS3k1Fg4y5tAhLbw

2.1 Linear Regression 

lr = LinearRegression()
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = lr.predict(X_test)
print('Accuracy: ', lr.score(X_test, y_test))
print('Mean Absolute Error: ', mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred))
print('Mean Squared Error: ', mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
print('R Squared: ', r2_score(y_test, y_pred))
